<h3>Brief History Of AR</h3>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>1968</strong><strong>:</strong>&nbsp;Ivan Sutherland and Bob Sproull created the worldâ€™s first head-mounted display with primitive computer graphics.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong><em>The Sword of Damocles</em></strong><br><a href="https://www.softwaretestinghelp.com/wp-content/qa/uploads/2020/06/The-Sword-of-Damocles-worlds-first-headmounted-display-built-in-1968.jpg"></a></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><em>[image&nbsp;<a href="https://www.informit.com/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">source</a>]</em></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>1975</strong><strong>:&nbsp;</strong>Videoplace, an AR lab, is created by Myron Krueger. The mission was to have human movement interactions with digital stuff. This technology was later employed on projectors, cameras, and on-screen silhouettes.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong><em>Myron Krueger</em></strong><br><a href="https://www.softwaretestinghelp.com/wp-content/qa/uploads/2020/06/Myron-Krueger.jpg"></a></p>
